4. Reference Scope and Responsibility

Use of STOCRS-R is entirely at the user's own risk.

STOCRS-R is a bounded reference implementation and research model for deterministic structural resolution and versioned program evolution under the declared reference cases.

The current governing relation is:

same program identity + same declared inputs + same evidence + same available-node set + complete presentation of that set -> same supported values

For the complete semantic result:

same semantic resolution inputs + complete presentation of the same available-node set -> same state + same certificate

The current bounded reference model also demonstrates:

claim multiplicity != structural authority

declared program mutation -> changed canonical program payload -> new program identity -> deterministic new supported output

Within the declared reference cases, the implementation demonstrates explicit incompleteness, bounded conflict handling, deterministic result reproduction, versioned program identities, reproducible resolution certificates, and frozen file-identity verification.

The current reference implementation does not guarantee universal sequence independence, universal synchronization independence, automatic convergence of arbitrary distributed systems, communication-free operation, coordination-free operation, consensus, factual truth of inputs, network reliability, security, system-level fault tolerance, regulatory compliance, production readiness, or fitness for financial, medical, safety-critical, or other high-risk use.

Execution, sequencing, communication, networking, persistence, retries, scheduling, synchronization, coordination, orchestration, and other operational mechanisms may remain necessary in real systems.

The reference claim is limited to the declared STOCRS-R model and does not imply that those mechanisms are universally unnecessary.


